{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a31abc6a-4e43-4d1e-ab76-8ff1abca9489","content":"`dotnet-dump` is now installed and ready. Here's how to analyze your dump:\n\n### Quick start\n\n```bash\n# Open the dump in interactive mode\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your/file.dmp\n```\n\n### Key commands once inside the analyzer\n\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` or `printexception` | Show the last exception (crash cause) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` | Switch to a specific thread |\n| `clrstack` | Show managed call stack for current thread |\n| `clrstack -a` | Call stack with local variables |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for memory issues) |\n| `exit` | Quit the analyzer |\n\n### Recommended workflow\n1. Run `pe` first — it usually reveals the crashing exception immediately\n2. Run `threads` to find the faulting thread\n3. Use `setthread` + `clrstack` to inspect its stack\n\nIf you share the dump file path, I can run these commands for you interactively!","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"55e3d07c-9292-4bc1-8409-79d436d14b97","outputTokens":272,"requestId":"6083:32FC8B:3266CC:40F6DD:69FFE581"},"id":"b1449233-0b08-48f9-b48c-16b4d66b5bad","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:55:22.822Z","parentId":"25b9f8cd-fe7f-4058-ab84-7236386af143"}
